Abstract = {Hate speech through online social media is on the rise, which has
   attracted researchers across the world to develop models to control its
   circulation to create better and smarter society. Although several
   models have been reported to recognize hate speech in the most widely
   spoken language, the issue has not yet been deemed to be under control.
   Very few academics have built models to identify hate speech spreaders
   so that the problem can be managed at the source by correctly filtering
   their posts. In this article, we employ long short-term memory (LSTM) to
   extract features from user-posted text-tweet and Tweepy to extract
   behavior-based features. The LSTM-based textual feature extracted from
   text-tweet and user behavior based features extracted from the Twitter
   user's profile are concatenated and further optimized with camel
   algorithm (CA) to yield more pertinent features. The optimized feature
   vector is used to determine whether or not a user is a hate spreader
   using machine learning classifiers. The developed model is validated
   with the dataset provided by the PAN 2021 and PAN-2020
   (https://pan.webis.de/data.html) hate speech spreader profiling and
   FakeNews spreader profiling challenge, respectively. Our proposed model
   outperforms the state-of-the-art models, with an accuracy of 96\% for
   PAN 2021 and 94\% for PAN 2020 for English and Spanish datasets,
   respectively.},
